{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"82abe4db-ae98-4285-8b1b-128597265c2a","content":"## Analyzing .NET GC on Linux\n\n**Collect a GC trace with `dotnet-trace`:**\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (once)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Collect GC events from your running process\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile gc-verbose\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **PerfView** (Windows) or convert:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert <file>.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\n\n**For real-time GC stats:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\n\nKey counters to watch: `gc-heap-size`, `gen-0/1/2-gc-count`, `time-in-gc`.\n\n**For GC dump analysis:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-gcdump\ndotnet-gcdump collect -p <PID>\n```\n\n**Quick wins to reduce pauses:**\n- Set **Server GC** in your `.csproj`: `<ServerGarbageCollection>true</ServerGarbageCollection>`\n- Or via env var: `DOTNET_gcServer=1`\n- Consider `DOTNET_GCDynamicAdaptationMode=1` (.NET 8+) for dynamic tuning","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cc65e2bb-1f08-4c53-bcdb-33ab4d7af944","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET GC diagnostics on Linux. This is a knowledge question — no codebase work needed. I'll provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":387},"id":"8ff5956b-2211-4687-880f-6da385bfb148","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:40:18.675Z","parentId":"195d62fc-949d-4f21-9f0a-0692dd24ceb7"}
